node.text: I know we are all struggling during these challenging times. I wanted to share parts of a highschool speech I gave pre-covid. In a sense, the whole world is experiencing forms of grief right now. I hope by vulnerably speaking about my life journey you gain self-help, comfort, motivation, and coping  skills. My goal is to save one life out there. Mental health is real. You are not alone. Please don’t be afraid to talk about it and ask for help! Much love to you all. Thank you @southbayfamiliesconnected for this opportunity. This version was cut, and shortened to fit Instagram’s time frame. Please the website www.southbay familiesconnected.org for the full video. Thank you @annie.graziano with the editing help.

node.text: Link in Bio. Growing up, I had never heard of mental health. I didn’t know what anxiety and depression were. I now realize I have struggled with them for as long as I can remember. I’ll even say I have sleep issues including insomnia. It can be a very vicious cycle. Although it’s very uncomfortable, I continue moving forward sharing vulnerably. I always thought I had to publicly be “okay”. But it’s okay to not be okay. We can do it together. I know many of our emotions are heightened during this troubling time of loss, fear, stress, anxiety, depression... I’d like to share with you my journey, and the tools I’ve used to stay mentally healthy. Please join Beach Cities Health District, SouthBay Families Connected, Kevin Sousa, and me tomorrow Thursday April 29th @ 6 pm US PST for a viral chat on all of these subjects. Again, you can sign up via the link in my Instagram bio. Thanks.

node.text:
Happy 4th of July from the green room. This was so funny filming, and way harder than I ever expected. @nuttynulty and I were down in Mexico filming for a TURKEYMELT episode. The swell was a few days before July 4th. So we figured why not bring an Uncle Sam suit, some American flags, and get barreled in it?! But that wasn’t enough... I really wanted to get barreled with a firecracker as well. Our main man @sacraficialamb knew of a fireworks dealer down a dirt road. What I didn’t realize is how hard it would be to light a firecracker out on the ocean. We were doing step offs with a jetski to get into the waves.The idea was to light the firework, then step off onto my board and into the tube with the fire stacker going off. Not that simple. Of course out on the water it was wet and windy. So the only way was to light it behind the car door on the beach, then run across the beach with it lit, jump onto Justin’s ski in the shorebreak, zoom out to the lineup and jump into a wave before it firecracker went out... thank god we bought about 20 of these little guys. This is one of my favorite memories from shenanigans on the road :) Sorry for burning a few holes on your jetski seat Justin!
Thanks @nuttynulty for always being into filming and creating weird, fun stuff. And my good friend @jasehen87 who played the guitar for this tune.

node.text: :) I’ve never imagined traveling not being in my life. This month marks an entire year without getting on a plane, or traveling anywhere for that matter. I’ve just been home. Traveling has been the major part of my life for the last 20 years. Many of those years I was gone 9 out of the 12 months chasing the dream of waves and accolades. When covid hit, most of my financial avenues came to a halt. I stayed “safe” by staying home. I thought it would be a month or two. I honestly never imagined it being a year to the date. I went into a depression from things being taken away. I was fighting to control not having to let go of normal life to save money. I was also living in fear mixed with anxiety of how to cope moving forward. I’ve never been good at sitting, or even staying in one place. Everyday I woke up hoping to find acceptance in losing the aspects which give me purpose in life. I realized that grief spans further than just loss of a loved one. It took me months to just let this all be. It felt like I was only living in survival mode. I realized I put way to much pressure on myself to allow true happiness in my life outside of it being from accomplishments. I was stuck in a very uncomfortable place as I know a lot of you were, and still are. I feel you. But, I have to thank this past year for guiding me to create new businesses. There’s been a lot of doubt and lack of confidence with my typical emotional armor taken off. I’ve had to face every aspect of myself, especially the parts I’m not the most proud of. And geez having to do so emotionally with nowhere to run or hide isn’t that fun. But it’s important work. Maybe the most important of all. I think a lot of my travels actually allowed me to avoid myself. Unexpectedly, I’ve found a lot of growth and gratitude in the stillness of this past year. I am looking forward to traveling again soon. I hope you’re all doing alright out there. It’s been a trip. Photo: @chrisburkard
